# React 19

Project uses React 19. Prefer the new primitives below over older patterns.

## `use()` for Promises & Context

`use()` unwraps a promise or reads a context. It can be called inside Suspense and conditionally (unlike other hooks).

```tsx
"use client";
import { use } from "react";

export function Profile({ userPromise }: { userPromise: Promise<User> }) {
  const user = use(userPromise);
  return <p>{user.name}</p>;
}
```

## `ref` is a Prop (no `forwardRef`)

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
const Input = forwardRef<HTMLInputElement, Props>((props, ref) => <input ref={ref} {...props} />);

// ✅ GOOD
function Input({ ref, ...props }: Props & { ref?: React.Ref<HTMLInputElement> }) {
  return <input ref={ref} {...props} />;
}
```

## Form Actions

Pass a function to `<form action={...}>` for progressive-enhancement-friendly submissions.

```tsx
"use client";
import { useActionState } from "react";

async function submit(prev: State, formData: FormData) {
  // server action or async fn
}

export function MyForm() {
  const [state, formAction, isPending] = useActionState(submit, initialState);
  return <form action={formAction}>{/* ... */}</form>;
}
```

## `useOptimistic` for Optimistic UI

```tsx
const [optimisticList, addOptimistic] = useOptimistic(
  list,
  (state, newItem: Item) => [newItem, ...state],
);
```

## `useFormStatus` Inside `<form>` Children

```tsx
import { useFormStatus } from "react-dom";

function SubmitButton() {
  const { pending } = useFormStatus();
  return <button disabled={pending}>Send</button>;
}
```

## General Rules

- Avoid `useEffect` for derived state — compute during render.
- Keep effect dependencies narrow and correct.
- Use functional state updates (`setX(prev => ...)`) when the next value depends on the previous one.
- Prefer explicit conditional rendering (`cond ? <X /> : null`) over `&&` when `cond` can be `0` or `""`.
- Don't barrel-import large modules into client components; import directly from source.
